{"cursor":"12014","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'Global-warming potential' (GWP) is a relative measure of how much heat a\ngreenhouse gas traps in the atmosphere. It compares the amount of heat trapped\nby a certain mass of the gas in question to the amount of heat trapped by a\nsimilar mass of carbon dioxide. A GWP is calculated over a specific time\ninterval, commonly 20, 100 or 500 years. GWP is expressed as a factor of carbon\ndioxide (whose GWP is standardized to 1). For example, the 20 year GWP of\nmethane is 72, which means that if the same mass of methane and carbon dioxide\nwere introduced into the atmosphere, that methane will trap 72 times more heat\nthan the carbon dioxide over the next 20 years.\n\nThe substances subject to restrictions under the Kyoto protocol either are\nrapidly increasing their concentrations in Earth's atmosphere or have a\nlarge GWP.\n\nThe GWP depends on the following factors:\n* the absorption of infrared radiation by a given species\n* the spectral location of its absorbing wavelengths\n* the atmospheric lifetime of the species Thus, a high GWP correlates with a\n  large infrared absorption and a long atmospheric lifetime. The dependence of\n  GWP on the wavelength of absorption is more complicated. Even if a gas absorbs\n  radiation efficiently at a certain wavelength, this may not affect its GWP\n  much if the atmosphere already absorbs most radiation at that wavelength. A\n  gas has the most effect if it absorbs in a \"window\" of wavelengths where the\n  atmosphere is fairly transparent. The dependence of GWP as a function of\n  wavelength has been found empirically and published as a\n  graph. [http://www.chem.tamu.edu/rgroup/north/ITS%20GWP%20Data.xls Matthew\n  Elrod, \"Greenhouse Warming Potential Model.\"] Based on Journal of Chemical\n  Education, Vol 76, pp. 1702â1705, December 1999\n\nBecause the GWP of a greenhouse gas depends directly on its infrared spectrum,\nthe use of infrared spectroscopy to study greenhouse gases is centrally\nimportant in the effort to understand the impact of human activities on global\nclimate change.\n","linknr":345,"url":"global_warming_potential","recorded":1376420175,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Global-warming_potential&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Global-warming_potential&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Global-warming_potential","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Global_warming_potential&redirect=no","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:Translation_to_english_arrow.svg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Translation_to_english_arrow.svg/50px-Translation_to_english_arrow.svg.png","//de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treibhauspotenzial","//de.wikipedia.org/wiki/","http://translate.google.com/translate?&u=http%3A%2F%2Fde.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FTreibhauspotenzial&sl=de&tl=en","/wiki/Talk:Global-warming_potential","/wiki/Wikipedia:Copying_within_Wikipedia","/wiki/Wikipedia:Translation","/wiki/Greenhouse_gas","/wiki/Gas","/wiki/Carbon_dioxide","/wiki/Methane","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Kyoto_protocol","/wiki/Earth%27s_atmosphere","/wiki/Infrared_radiation","/wiki/Atmospheric_lifetime","#cite_note-2","/wiki/Infrared_spectroscopy","/wiki/Climate_change","#Calculating_the_global-warmin